\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Gyroscopic controls applied to a desktop application context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Seirra Blake
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DidOS (shorthand version of Didelphimorphic OS) is an operating system distribut
ion currently in development.
 One way the creators want it to improve upon the current graphical user
 interface experience is by integrating gyroscopic controls to allow a near
 frictionless user input experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Inspiration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This concept was inspired by a brief video essay that explored the topic,
 with a context towards videogame user input.
 During the video essay, a test was done with multiple input devices; the
 test that was carried out involved aiming a virtual gun at a target, an
 experience that is analogous to a lot of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

first person shooter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (also known as FPS) videogames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Supporting evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I hypothesise that the benefits seen in FPS videogames when gyroscopic controls
 are used to aim could also translate to a desktop PC experience.
 I hypothesise that users will give positive testimonials, including digital
 artists, if available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
References
\end_layout

